Wrestling with Data: Is Push Sumo Streaky?

Eugene Domrachev, Si Young Sung, I.K. Atupulazi

Introduction¶

Sumo wrestling is a very simple sport. Each bout (fight) is held inside of a ring. If a fighter touches the ground inside the ring with anything but their feet, they lose. If they land outside of the ring, they also lose. Despite this simplicity, sumo has many intricacies in its execution. One such intricacy is the fighting style which a particular wrestler takes. Sumo has two main fighting styles:

Yotsu-zum Oshi-zum
A belt-oriented fighting style. A belt, or a mawashi, is the only thing a wrestler wears when competing, so it becomes a target for those looking for a grip on their opponent. Accordingly, practicioners of this style usually win by forcing their opponent out (or down) by their belt. A beltless fighting style, focused on pushing the opponent out of the ring without using the mawashi. This includes shoves, face slaps, and a barrage of arm thrusts.

Currently, there are several prolific thrusters in sumo's top division. Two of these wrestlers are Daieisho and Takakeisho -- who both recently won a tournament, then followed up with a middling or poor performance. Meanwhile, a yotsu practicioner, Terunofuji, has been on a ridiculously consistent tear in the past year. Recent happenings likethis has prompted many to wonder if pushers are actually streaky between tournaments.. In this project, we will attempt to give mathematical insight into this question by looking at the tournaments in the top two (salaried) divisions of sumo.

Glossary (read for best results!!)¶

  • Oshi-zum/Oshi sumo/oshi - style of sumo which involves a lot of pushing/thrusting techniques
  • Yotsu-zum/Yotsu sumo/yotsu - style of sumo focused on gripping the belt and utilizing continued contact to force displace other wrestlers
  • Mawashi - The belt each rikishi wears
  • Rikishi - A sumo wrestler
  • Shikona - A wrestler's ring name. Rikishi have symbolic names that they take on for competition purposes, which usually differ from their real name
  • Basho - The bimonthly official tournament, where wrestlers fight for 7 or 15 days depending on their divisions.
  • Kimarite - Winning move of a bout. This can be something like frontal push out (oshidashi) or overarm throw (uwatenage). Here is a list of all recognized kimarite.
  • Jury - The second division from the top. Will be part of our analysis
  • Makuuchi - The first (and top) division
  • Maegashira - The name of the ranks inside makuuchi
  • Sanyaku - The elite ranks of the top division. These sit above the maegashira ranks.



Section 1: Pusher Metric

</h1>

Creating a pusher metric¶

To begin answering our target question, we have to talk about how to observe a pushing style from data. Our data source, sumodb, has a record of the winning moves (kimarite) a rikishi has used in their career. To score someone on their oshi-ness, we can compute the proportion of push-based moves to all winning moves. Say the number of all wins is $n$, and call this $p$.

That is to say, $\quad p = \frac{\text{# winning oshi moves}}{n}\quad$ so we can then define $m$, the pusher metric, as follows: $\quad m = (0.5 - p) \cdot log(n)$

It can be easily seen that those who tend towards push sumo will receive a negative score, while those who tend away from it will have a positive score.

Some rationale for the formula:

  1. If a wrestler is dead even between oshi and another other style, we want their score to be zero. This is the reason for the $0.5$ term.
  2. We want to give confidence to wrestlers with high win volume in whichever direction they lean, but in a limited fashion. Hence, the $log(n)$ term.


Why not make this a binary metric?

Wrestlers sometimes transition in their fighting style. Wrestlers like Akebono, Musashimaru, and Asashoryu used to be oshi specialists, but picked up the yotsu style as they rose through the ranks and sustained injuries. For these wrestlers, it would be innacurate to classify them as one or the other (although we will be looking into this later), so giving a confidence-based estimate is a good option here.

To make sure this is an apt measure of oshi, let's do a sanity check by testing it on some known wrestlers. The oshi moves of a wrestler will be plotted in red, and others will be in blue.

"""
Take in a list of wrestlers by their shikona, and output a list of lists containing the wrestler's 
significant winning moves.
"""
def kimarite_list_by_name(rikishi_list):

    base_URL = "http://sumodb.sumogames.de/"
    shikona_search_URL = "http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi.aspx?shikona="

    # this will look like  [ ("Takakeisho", [url_to_kimarite]),  ... ]
    kimarite_URL_collection = []

    for rikishi in rikishi_list:
        

        # get the wrestler's page by searching their name
        basepage = requests.get(shikona_search_URL + rikishi)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(basepage.content, 'html.parser')
        
        # if shikona is unique, there will by a 'bouts by kimarite' link
        kimarite_page = soup.find('a', href = re.compile(r'Rikishi_kim*'))

        # if it's not unique, you will come to a page with a table of wrestlers
        # with this shikona by date. get the latest one by date
        # example: http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi.aspx?shikona=Terao
        if not kimarite_page:
            #print(f"non-unique shikona found ({rikishi})...")
            kimarite_page = soup.find('tbody').findAll('a', href = re.compile(r'Rikishi.aspx'))
            basepage = requests.get("http://sumodb.sumogames.de/" + kimarite_page[-1]['href'])
            soup = BeautifulSoup(basepage.content, 'html.parser')
            kimarite_page = soup.find('a', href = re.compile(r'Rikishi_kim*'))
        
        #print(kimarite_page['href'])
        kimarite_URL_collection.append( (rikishi, base_URL + kimarite_page['href']) )



    # pie chart requires size and label lists. so, we will make a list like 
    # [ ( "Name", [kimarite_name, ...], [kimarite_amt, ...] ),   ... ] 
    kimarite = []

    for (shikona, kimarite_URL) in kimarite_URL_collection:
        print(f"processing {shikona}...")
        basepage = requests.get(kimarite_URL)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(basepage.content, 'html.parser')
    
        # get winning data table 
        kimarite_wins = soup.find('table', class_="ro_left")
            
        # this gets all winning moves in like 
        # [<tr><td class="rb_kim">oshidashi</td><td class="right"><a href="#0oshidashi">143</a></td></tr>, ...]
        cells = kimarite_wins.find_all('tr')

        kimarite_labels, kimarite_amts = [], []

        for cell in cells:
            win_name_tag, win_amt_tag = cell.find_all('td')
            kimarite_labels.append(win_name_tag.text.strip())
            kimarite_amts.append(int(win_amt_tag.text.strip()))
        

        # at this point we have all kimarite. reduce it so that only moves with >= 5% significance are displayed
        up_to_index = 0
        total_wins = sum(kimarite_amts)
        for i in range(0, len(kimarite_amts)):
            amt = kimarite_amts[i]
            # we find the most significant kimarite under 10%
            if amt / total_wins < 0.05:
                up_to_index = i
                break

        # we now slice off everything up to and past this point, label it as 'other'
        kimarite_labels = kimarite_labels[:up_to_index] + ["other"]
        kimarite_amts = kimarite_amts[:up_to_index] + [sum(kimarite_amts[up_to_index:])]
        
        kimarite.append((shikona, kimarite_labels, kimarite_amts))

    print("done extracting kimarite!")
    return kimarite

def make_graphs(fighters):

    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5, wspace=0.3)
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20, math.ceil(len(fighters)/4)*5)


    fig, axs = plt.subplots(math.ceil(len(fighters)/4), 4)
    fig.suptitle('Wrestlers wins by kimarite & oshi classification', fontsize=20)
    axs = axs.flatten()
    ai = 0
    
    # this is auxiliary for exploration into kimarite category.
    # we only care about oshi/non oshi, so we don't use this... but you might :)
    color_group_general = {
                'Kihonwaza: Basic technique': 'red',
                'Nagete: Throwing technique': 'blue',
                'Kakete: Leg tripping technique': 'green',
                'Hinerite: Twist down technique': 'black',
                'Sorite: Backwards body drop': 'brown',
                'Tokushuwaza: Special technique': 'yellow',
                'Higi: Non-technique': 'gray',
                'Others': 'gray',
                None: 'gray'
    } 


    for (rikishi, kimarite_labels, kimarite_amts) in kimarite_list_by_name(fighters):

        ax1 = axs[ai]

        n = sum(kimarite_amts)
        w = 0 
        for i in range(0, len(kimarite_amts)):
            w += kimarite_amts[i] if kimarite_helper.is_oshi(kimarite_labels[i]) else 0
        p = w / n

        # explode top three kimarite
        explode = tuple( [0.05]*3 + ([0] * (len(kimarite_labels)-3)) )
        
        #colors = [color_group_general[kimarite_helper.classify(x)] for x in kimarite_labels]
        # highlighting OSHI in RED
        colors = ['red' if kimarite_helper.is_oshi(x) else 'blue' for x in kimarite_labels]

        ax1.pie(kimarite_amts, explode=explode, labels=kimarite_labels, autopct='%1.1f%%',
                shadow=True, startangle=90, #textprops={'color':"b"}, 
                #colors=map(lambda x: color_d[kimarite_helper.classify(x)], kimarite_labels)
                colors=colors
                )
        ax1.title.set_color('black')
        ax1.axis('equal')  
        ax1.set_title( rikishi + " (n=%s, p=%s, m=%s" % (n, "{:.2f}".format(p), "{:.2f}".format((0.5 - p)  * math.log10(n))) + ")")
        
        ai += 1
    
    while ai < 4 * math.ceil(len(fighters)/4):
        axs[ai].axis('off')
        ai += 1
    
    plt.show()

Considerations on the m metric¶

  1. The unrestricted $log(n)$ term should be monitored. In practice, Hakuho, the most winning wrestler in sumo history, has won about 1200 bouts, and has an $m$ of 1.00. Furthermore, the m distribution will be within an appropriate range, which will be shown post data scraping.

  2. The metric shows an oshi tendency or lack thereof, but NOT necessarily a yotsu tendency. Non-oshi kimarite are not exclusively yotsu, there are are some specialized throw techniques and non-techniques that are not commonly used in yotsu. For this reason, m should be thought of a measure of "oshi and non-oshi."

  3. Some fighters, Like Akebono and Musashimaru, transitionitioned from an oshi to a yotsu style throughout their career. Shouldn't we keep track of m up to any date as you're scraping wrestler information? Yes, we should. However, this would extend the runtime of scraping by a significant amount. The plan to scrape wrestler information is as follows:

    • Access their page by an increasing rikisihi ID (as defined by sumodb).
    • Read their basic tournament history on this page (has W/L, but NOT kimarite).
    • Once this is all done, create a different dataframe with the metrics calculated by accessing the kimarite page of relevant scraped wrestlers.

The first two steps alone takes around 13,000 requests, which is a significant amount of time to process. Adding another request to each basho's page for that wrestler (which DOES have kimarite) would increase that number many times. For the scope of this project, we will not consider the changing $m$ score, but compute it only for a wrestler's career.



Part 2: Scraping for all wrestler data


Our plan for data¶

Before we get going, we should clearly define what we want, how we're going to get it, and how we'll deal with missing data.

What¶

In our analysis for "streakiness," we are going to be looking at performances at consecutive tournaments. So, we need a dataframe with all the tournament histories that we care about. That being said, we only care about the histories of wrestlers which have reached the top two divisions (this is defined in the scope of our question). We will ignore those who have their career high rank below those two divisions.

How¶

To get this data, we visit a wrestler's page by an integer ID. Once there, their highest rank, as well as tournament history, is displayed in a table. First, check that a wrestler has reached the top two divisions. If not, skip them. Otherwise, process their tournament table. An example of a wrestler page can be seen here.

Missing data¶

Some rikishi have missing win/loss order records for their tournament data. In this case, the kimarite used in the tournament is not recorded. Take this page as an example. If we see any missing rows, we drop the wrestler from processing as we do not have a way to accurately calculate their $m$ score. Imputing a mean or empty value would take away from the analysis on the $m$ distribution.


Let's get started!

Scraping all tournament data¶

"""
Get the dataframe with all of a wrestler's tournaments.
Each row will be one of their tournament performances.
"""

def get_df_by_id(id):
    
    # example page: http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi.aspx?r=1123

    URL = f"http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi.aspx?r={id}"
    basepage = requests.get(URL)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(basepage.content, 'html.parser')
    
    # find the wrestler's top career rank
    try:
        highest = soup.find('table', class_='rikishidata')
        highest = highest.find('table', class_='rikishidata')
        highest = highest.find('tr').findAll('td')[1].contents[0]
        highest = str(highest.split()[0]).replace('-', '')
    except:
        print(f"{id} skipped prelim")
        return
    
    # we're only considering those who made it to the top division
    if not rank_helper.rank_is_top(highest, True):
        print(f"{id} rejected")
        return 


    get_data = soup.find_all('tr')


    # texts that we have to convert, since it's an image in the table
    txt1 = '<img border="0" src="img/hoshi_shiro.gif"/>'     # win, white circle
    txt2 = '<img border="0" src="img/hoshi_yasumi.gif"/>'    # withdrawal, dash
    txt3 = '<img border="0" src="img/hoshi_kuro.gif"/>'      # loss, black circle
    txt4 = '<img border="0" src="img/hoshi_fusenpai.gif"/>'  # ff, black square
    txt5 = '<img border="0" src="img/hoshi_fusensho.gif"/>'  # hoshi_fusensho, opp withdrawal, white square


    # convert the images to W(win) F(forfeit) L(loss)
    edited = str(get_data).replace(txt1, 'W')
    edited = edited.replace(txt2, 'F')
    edited = edited.replace(txt3, 'L')
    edited = edited.replace(txt4, 'A') # absence means a loss, but we count it as something separate
    edited = edited.replace(txt5, 'W') # enemy ff counts as win


    # put the record table into a dataframe
    test = pd.read_html(edited)
    df = test[2]

    # rename columns
    df.columns = ['Date','Rank', 'Series','W_L','Yusho_standing', 'Height/weight']
    
    # if there is no series, there is no relevant data here most likely (record too old, mae-zumo)
    # example: http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi.aspx?r=11111
    # this rikishi has no kimarite data anyhow, so we don't need them in the final dataframe.
    df.dropna(subset = ["Series"], inplace=True)

    # drop any possible name-change banner columns
    df = df[df.W_L.apply(lambda x: '-' in x)]

    # convert dates to datetime
    df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'].astype(str), format='%Y.%m')

    # we don't really care about yusho standing and height/weight. drop them
    df = df.drop(columns=['Yusho_standing', 'Height/weight'])


    # calculate streaks
    forfeit_list = []
    win_list = []
    lose_list = []
    ab_list = []
    streak_list = []

    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        f_count = 0
        w_count = 0
        l_count = 0
        a_count = 0
        row_series = row['Series']


        # get W/L/F/A by counting
        for s in row_series:
            if(s == 'F'):
                f_count += 1 
            if(s == 'W'):
                w_count += 1
            if(s == 'L'):
                l_count += 1
            if(s == 'A'):
                a_count += 1

        forfeit_list.append(f_count)
        win_list.append(w_count)
        lose_list.append(l_count)
        ab_list.append(a_count)

        # basho is a streak when you win 4 or more bouts in a row
        streak_list.append(sum(1 for x in re.finditer(r'W{4,}', row['Series'])))


    # make new columns
    df['Win'] = win_list
    df['Loss'] = lose_list
    df['Forfeit'] = forfeit_list
    df['Absence'] = ab_list



    # calculate win rate: (W/# bouts fought), ignoring the games forfeited
    df['Winrate'] = (df['Win']/(15 - (df['Forfeit'] + df['Absence'])))*100
    # remove nans
    df['Winrate'] = df['Winrate'].replace(np.nan,0)
    # round the numbers to the 2 decimal place
    df['Winrate'] = df['Winrate'].round(2)


    # change streak column to Y or N
    change = []
    for s in streak_list:
        if(s > 0):
            change.append('Y')
        else:
            change.append('N')


    df['Streak(Wins)'] = change
    # apply the sumodb id to all columns
    df.insert(0, 'id', id)
        

    return df

Get the push score (m), push win% (p), and number of wins (n) of a given wrestler by their ID.
"""
def get_m_by_id(id):
    
    kimarite_URL = f"http://sumodb.sumogames.de/Rikishi_kim.aspx?r={id}"
    print(f"processing {id}...")
    basepage = requests.get(kimarite_URL)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(basepage.content, 'html.parser')

    # get winning data table 
    kimarite_wins = soup.find('table', class_="ro_left")

    # this gets all winning moves in like
    #[<tr><td class="rb_kim">oshidashi</td><td class="right"><a href="#0oshidashi">143</a></td></tr>, ...]
    cells = kimarite_wins.find_all('tr')

    kimarite_labels, kimarite_amts = [], []

    for cell in cells:
        win_name_tag, win_amt_tag = cell.find_all('td')
        kimarite_labels.append(win_name_tag.text.strip())
        kimarite_amts.append(int(win_amt_tag.text.strip()))


    # at this point we have all kimarite. reduce it so that only moves with >= 5% significance are displayed
    up_to_index = 0
    total_wins = sum(kimarite_amts)
    for i in range(0, len(kimarite_amts)):
        amt = kimarite_amts[i]
        # we find the most significant kimarite under 5%
        if amt / total_wins < 0.05:
            up_to_index = i
            break

    # we now slice off everything up to and past this point, label it as 'other'
    kimarite_labels = kimarite_labels[:up_to_index] + ["other"]
    kimarite_amts = kimarite_amts[:up_to_index] + [sum(kimarite_amts[up_to_index:])]

    #print((shikona, kimarite_amts, kimarite_labels))
    
    n = sum(kimarite_amts)
    if n == 0:
        return (None, None, None)
        
    w = 0 
    for i in range(0, len(kimarite_amts)):
        w += kimarite_amts[i] if kimarite_helper.is_oshi(kimarite_labels[i]) else 0
    
    p = w / n
    m = (0.5 - p)  * math.log10(n)
    return (m, p, n)

Considerations in scraping¶

  1. We are ONLY analyzing those who made it to the top division with more than five tournaments recorded. This lets us have confidence in the wrestler's $m$ score.
  2. We are NOT analyzing old records. This information does not have kimarite recorded, so we have no idea whether these wrestlers were pushers or not. As such, we drop them from our analysis. We lose the information of many old bouts.
  3. We are classifying pushers only by winning techniques. For further analysis, we could also look into how pushers tend to lose their bouts, and factor that into their m score.

    elif score < 0:

    elif score < 0.2:
        return 'Moderate other'
    else:

Bucketed win visualization (human cutoffs)¶

In [1637]:
"""
This code looks processes X **consecutive** tournaments based on an origin "bucket."
These buckets are defined by wins, with the following cutoffs:
    bad/low score: wins < 6 
    ok/mid score: 6 <= wins <= 10  
    good/high score: wins > 11
It then returns the average run of the tournament series, for each frame passed,
and for each origin bucket.
    
frames is the selected tournament data of each category to be processed.
window is the amount of consecutive tournaments to look at.
    for example, window=2 only looks at a tournament and the next performance.
"""
    
def compute_runs(frames, window):
    
    sig_wins_high = 11
    sig_wins_low = 6

    
    l = len(frames)
    
    # get WIN HISTORY of three tourneys from starting point of low wins, med wins, high wins
    # [ [low_1, low_2, low_3, n]    [...]    [...]]
    scopes = [ [[0] * (window+1) for i in range(0, 3)] for j in range(0, l) ]
    
    # get the DIFFERENCE of wins in basho
    diff = [ [[] * l for i in range(0, 3)] for j in range(0, l) ]
    
    sec_in_months = 2629800
    

    # for each frame, 
    for m in range(0, l):

        # for each id, 
        for w_id, group in frames[m].groupby("id"):

            # reset index to make sure we can access consecutive rows
            group.reset_index(inplace=True)

            # for each tournament, 
            for i, row in group.iterrows():

                if i < group.shape[0] - (window-1): # make sure we're not trying to grab data past the last two basho

                    # find which win bucket this basho belongs to
                    k = 0
                    if row.Win < sig_wins_low: # low w
                        k = 0
                    elif row.Win < sig_wins_high: # med w
                        k = 1
                    else: # high w 
                        k = 2

                    # setting the win differential for the next row 
                    diff[m][k].append(group['Win'].iat[i] - group['Win'].iat[i+1])

                    # we should only be recording CONSECUTIVE bashos. check for this by 
                    # seeing how long it is between the first and third basho.
                    # they happen every two months, so the time span should be four months.
                    td = abs(group['Date'].iat[i+window-1] - group['Date'].iat[i])
                    
                    # the time diff has to be within two months * window
                    if td.total_seconds() < 2 * sec_in_months * (window-1) + 604800:
                        for pos in range(window):
                            scopes[m][k][pos] += group['Win'].iat[i+pos]

                        scopes[m][k][window] += 1
                    else:
                        pass
                    

    # calculating averages after summing the tournament types
    res = [ [[0] * window for i in range(0, 3)] for j in range(0, l) ]

    for m in range(0, l):
        for i in range(0, 3):
            for j in range(0, window):
                res[m][i][j] = scopes[m][i][j] / scopes[m][i][window]

        
                    
    return(res, diff)

Pusher classification by logistic regression¶

The cutoffs for classification were somewhat arbitrary: let's try to classify our wrestlers automatically. Since we have two supposed classes, we can try using logistic regression to classify our data by the $m$ feature. This method requires a training dataset, which is equivalent to the pushers and non_pushers in the exploratory analysis from section 1.

def push_class_logistic(data):
    
    # this is with accordance to the exploratory scraping in section 1
    pusherID = [12191,11985,8,12094,12043,11855,12239,5944,11934,7240]
    nonID = [11927,1123,12451,11868,1111,12107,12412,6599,11728,878,4,1]
    
    data['push_class_numeric'] = np.nan
    
    # initializing our training data
    for i, row in data.iterrows():
        if int(row['id']) in  pusherID:
            data.loc[i,"push_class_numeric"] = 0
        elif row['id'] in  nonID:
            data.loc[i,"push_class_numeric"] = 1

    # defining the training df
    df = data.loc[data['id'].isin(pusherID) | data['id'].isin(nonID)]

    # making our training set
    train_targ = df["push_class_numeric"].values
    train_feat = [[m] for m in df["m"]]
    
    # fitting the model
    lr = LogisticRegression()
    lr.fit(train_feat, train_targ)
    #print(lr.predict(test_feat)

    data.drop(['push_class_numeric'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    y_km = lr.predict([[m] for m in data["m"]])
    arr1 = ['Pusher' if i == 0 else 'Non-Pusher' for i in y_km]     
    return(arr1)


stats_df['push_class_LogisticRegression'] = push_class_logistic(stats_df)

Classification with k-means clustering¶

There is an alternative to logistic regression in this scenario. Instead of using a supervised regression algorithm, we can also attempt to use an unsupervised clustering algorithm for classification. This may fit our data better. Initially, we had full and moderate classes for each style, resulting in four total classifications. Maybe we can replicate those results.

We will attempt k-means clustering for up to four clusters.

In [1649]:
# fit k-means to the m score
def push_class_kmeans(data, k):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    arr = [[0, i] for i in data['m']]
    y_km = kmeans.fit_predict(arr)
    return(y_km)

Overall, this doesn't seem to be a good algorithm for this classification task. This is because the algorithm searches for local means: in our data, the pushers do not have a pronounced cluster, while the other styles do. This results in an expansive boundary for k=2, as seen in the top left. Increasing cluster size does not yield meaningful results. Logistic regression would be the best option for dividing the dataset into classes based on $m$ score, but if other features were included, perhaps k-means would prove to be more meaningful.

Section 5: Prediction

Fitting a prediction model and Null Hypothesis¶

Another way of determining whether or not pushers are streaky is to make a prediction model with multiple variables and look at the relationship between all of the variables and see if it is any different from pushers and non-pushers. However, due note that it will be very hard to accurately predict expected wins for the sumo tournament, since there are lots of external factors that could affect the player's wins in a tournament that we don't have the data on (such as player injury, condition on that day, etc). Hopefully, we see a p-value < 0.05, so that we can show that all of the variables are somewhat correlated.

Prepping the dataframe¶

In order to do our best effort on accurately predicting a player's expected wins based on their fields, we will include as much variables that we think that might affect the player's expected wins:

  • m-scores
  • Division of the player
  • Rank in the division
  • Previous wins (in the tournament before)

In order to use all these data in a model, we will need to do some prepping for the dataframe.

full['prev_wins'] = np.nan

# getting previous tournament wins (less than 2 months apart)

    if i < full.shape[0] - 1:

            td = abs(full['Date'].iat[i+1] - full['Date'].iat[i])  
            if td.total_seconds() < 5616000: # diff is less than 65 days (2 months 5 days)
                full['prev_wins'].iat[i+1] = full['Win'].iat[i]

Fitting a prediction model for the pushers¶

Since we are dealing with pushers and non-pushers, it will be appropriate to create two prediction model, so that we can compare the difference between the two.

Like we have mentioned above, the major variables that we think that will affect the expected wins are

  • m-score
  • division
  • rank in the division
  • wins in previous tournament

So the equation of the regression will be: $\text{Expected Wins} = m(x) + div(x) + rank(x) + prev\_wins(x)$

Trouble afoot¶

Every variables that we have put into the model is statistically significant or close to being statistically significant: except for the m-score, which has a p value of 0.227. This does make sense, as we based the classification with the m-score and since it's much higher than the 95% confidence level that we are aiming for, it will be better if we take the m-score off from the formula.

So now, the equation of the formula will be:

$\text{Expected Wins} = div(x) + rank(x) + prev\_wins(x)$

What can we see from the Model?¶

We can see that all of the p-values are less than zero, which means that this prediction model is more accurate than the one about the pushers. However, we do see a low $R^2$ value from both of the models.

From the parameters that we got from the output, we can see that:

  • The expected wins in Juryo division is 6.8784 (this is the dummy variable)
  • If the player is in Komusubi division, then the player is expected to lose 0.6450 more bouts than people in Juryo division
  • ...
  • As the rank in the division increases, the expected win increases by 0.0349
  • As you have more previous tournament wins, the expected win increases by 0.0362

Is there any difference between the two models? What does it tell us?¶

As we can see from the parameters of the two models, we can clearly see that all the variables are pretty similar in values between the two models. However, we do see a change in correlation between previous tournament wins. In the pusher prediction model, we saw that as the previous tournament wins increased, the expected win decreased. However, in the non-pusher prediction model, we saw that as the previous tournament wins increased, the expected win increased. With this fact, we can guess that pushers tend to lose more games after winning a lot of games and non-pushers tend to win more games after winning a lot of games. This could also mean that non-pushers are a lot more stable at getting wins than the pushers. However, we cannot conclude with this fact, since our $R^2$ value is low.

How does our model do in regards of prediction?¶

Let's visualize how well did our prediction model do in regards of predicting a player's expected wins. In order to visualize it, we must first calculate the residual. We can calculate the residual by subtracting the actual value from the predicted value. But guessing from the low $R^2$ value that we have gotten from the prediction model, it is very likely that it is not going to be very accurate.

$residual = actual - predicted$

# helper function to predict the values for the pushers
def predict_p(m,div,ranked,prev_wins):
    d = [['',0,0]]
    f1 = pd.DataFrame(d, columns = ['div','rank','prev_wins'])

    f1['div'].iat[0] = div
    f1['rank'].iat[0] = ranked 
    f1['prev_wins'].iat[0] = prev_wins

What can we see?¶

We can see that our residual graphs seems to be clustered around 0 and we don't see any obvious pattern inside the residuals, suggesting that the residuals follows most of the assumptions of the linear regression. Overall, this tells us that our prediction models did pretty well, in spite of having a low $R^2$ value.

Conclusion

From the tournament series, it is evident that pushers tend to lose more often in their tournament after performing well as compared to non-pushers. We observed this trend even in the yokozuna-less data. This helps us identify what many have noticed! The supposed pusher streakiness is exhibited by varying results after a high-profile tournament.

The cause for this result may have various potential sources, which cannot be observed within the present data:

  • The oshi style may be more inconsistent in win volume because of mechanical reasons.
  • Oshi sumo may be more susceptible to injuries, which hinders long term performance.
  • Those who are less versatile in winning techniques may be less consistent.

Ultimately, more analysis needs to be conducted to answer why this happens.

Match Fixing¶

In the early 2010s, there was a match-fixing scandal uncovered in Japanese sumo at large. Because retaining rank in the top two divisions offers significant benefits in terms of salary and rank within one's stable, there is much motivation to keep it. Wrestlers were found paying off others to throw matches so that they could stay in the top divisions. There was even formal analysis on the subject, which is available here.
